body:
In the example, to dump the vcd file, one need:

```cpp
topp->trace(tfp, 99); // Trace 99 levels of hierarchy
tfp->open("obj_dir/t_trace_ena_cc/simx.vcd");
```

However, if we reverse the two lines (_i.e._, call `open()` then `trace()`), the program crashes with an segmentation fault (when calling `dump()` later), which is hard to locate the reason.

```cpp
tfp->open("obj_dir/t_trace_ena_cc/simx.vcd");
topp->trace(tfp, 99); // Trace 99 levels of hierarchy
```

I am not sure whether this behaviour is documented somewhere.

A minimal reproducible example is:

```verilog
module Dummy(input clk);
endmodule
```

```cpp
#include "VDummy.h"
#include <verilated.h>
#include <verilated_vcd_c.h>
using namespace std;

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
        VerilatedContext ctx;
        VerilatedVcdC tfp;
        VDummy dut;
        ctx.traceEverOn(true);
        tfp.open("dump.vcd"); // Error! shall put to the next line!
        dut.trace(&tfp, 99); // Error!
        tfp.dump(0);
        tfp.close();
        return 0;
}
```

```bash
verilator --cc --trace --build --exe main.cpp Dummy.sv
./out_dir/VDummy
```

I think it would be easy to fix by checking `tfp->isOpen()` in `V3EmitC.cpp`.
